Tiverton, Devon, England":"Bradninch, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Normandie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Alain, Serge, Adrien, Andre, Aurore, Celine, Clovis, Emile, Gaetan, Gilles, Laurier.","French: from a diminutive of   Normand  . Compare   Normandy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Normand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Gaston, Andre, Laurent, Marcel, Pierre, Amie, Donat, Emile, Herve, Jacques, Jean Noel, Jean-Michel.","French and Breton (mainly Finistère; also <b>Le Normand</b>): habitational name for someone from Normandy, a region in northern France (see   Norman  ). Compare   Lenormand  .","Scottish (Fife): variant of   Norman  ."]},{"name":"Normandy","meanings":["English: habitational name from Normandy in northern France. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Americanized form of French   Normandin  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Normandie was born in 1080, in Normandy, France. She had at least 3 sons and 2 daughters with William de Tracy. She died in 1137, in Marcigny, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1080–1137":"1080–1137","1085–1162":"1085–1162","1103–1165":"1103–1165","1105–1140":"1105–1140","1123–Male":"1123–Surnud","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","1130–1224":"1130–1224","1080":"1080","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1085":"1085","Abt 1130":"umbes 1130","1105":"1105","1127":"1127","1137":"1137","1224":"1224","1103":"1103","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1123":"1123","about 1103":"umbes 1103","about 1123":"umbes 1123","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Bradninch, Devon, England":"Bradninch, Devon, England","Barnstaple, Devon, England":"Barnstaple, Devon, England","Marcigny, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, France":"Marcigny, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne-Franche-Comté, Prantsusmaa","Bradninch, Tiverton, Devon, England":"Bradninch, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1080–1137":"1080–1137","1085–1162":"1085–1162","1103–1165":"1103–1165","1105–1140":"1105–1140","1123–Male":"1123–Kuollut","1127–Female":"1127–Kuollut","1130–1224":"1130–1224","1080":"1080","1165":"1165","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","1085":"1085","Abt 1130":"noin 1130","1105":"1105","1127":"1127","1137":"1137","1224":"1224","1103":"1103","about 1127":"noin 1127","1123":"1123","abo